Executive Summary

This week, OSAC made significant progress on roadmap planning and
infrastructure
foundations. The team formalized release planning with three milestones:
0.1, 0.2, and 0.3, and organized features by release in Jira.

Planning for 0.1 is currently focused on core CaaS, VMaaS, and BMaaS
capabilities, while 0.2 and 0.3 are still in the initial planning stages
and will be expanded with additional features as the roadmap progresses.

Key demos included profile-based bare metal fulfillment for dynamic host
provisioning, catalog items for flexible cluster configuration, the new Enclave
UI wizard for simplifying disconnected environment setup, BCM integration
for server inventory management, and the new Helm-based OSAC installer for
OSAC installation.

The project also established a new workflow structure: Features contain
requirements and link to enhancement proposals on GitHub, which are then
broken down into Epics and Tasks. A new RFE ticket type will be added to
track external inputs from field teams before grooming them into formal
features.

Release 0.1: details
<https://redhat.atlassian.net/projects/OSAC/versions/105910/tab/release-report-all-issues?sortBy=STATUS>

0.1 Release Focus

   -

   Core capabilities: Multi-tenancy using Keycloak Organizations, tenant
   onboarding, and RBAC management.
   -

   VMaaS: VM lifecycle management, including create, delete, and restart;
   GPU passthrough; Windows VM support; dedicated VM clusters; graphical
   console access; and networking based on CUDN, with MetalLB used for public
   IPs.
   -

   CaaS: Cluster provisioning API, catalog items, DNS API, automatic agent
   provisioning, and networking integration. This includes integration with
   BCM for inventory, Netris for L3 tenant network isolation, Ansible
   Networking for worker VLAN isolation, Metal3 for provisioning, and VAST for
   storage.


